column41: My major challenge at UCLA has been navigating an institution both efficiently and strategically. There are many opportunities offered to Students of Color that it feels overwhelming how to go about the process of initiation.
column42: The best part of my UCLA experience has been building community and learning alongside my peers (whether it be through coursework or learning from their lived experiences).

column42: The best part of being at UCLA has been getting the support of my friends and peers that understand the struggle of being first-generation.
column43: Something that can improve my experience at UCLA would be having swipes for commuters or more support for commuters in terms of review sessions since they are mostly hosted late in the evening at the Hill and that poses a challenge because although they are beneficial for my grade I sometimes end up going home around 11 or 12pm.

column41: a major challenge is connecting with professors. in high school, it was easy to connect with teachers because they did not have many students. here, classes are usually over 200 students, and many office hours are always full, so that is what I find difficult. Also, it is really hard to find scholarships because I do not know where to look.
column42: the best part about my UCLA experience is joining the marching band because they are people that share a similar interest, and a large portion of them are STEM majors, so I know I can ask them for help with homework or other class-related material.
column43: I would like if it was made easier to find scholarships and clubs because I do not know where to look for either.

column41: Not feeling connected to UCLA which causes a lack of motivation.
column43: Better publicized resources that benefit underrepresented communities and UCLA sponsored events for those communities

column41: My major challenge at UCLA is that professors teach too quickly for me. I think that they assume that everyone is on the same higher level, when in reality I would like step by step instructions. In high school, my teachers would go through math step by step and I could easily follow along.
column42: The friends that I met my third year. Also a mentor that I gained by working for UCLA recreation. She changed my life and gave me confidence when I struggled severely my freshman and sophomore year.
column43: If I had met my friends earlier. Also, I should have joined a business related club since it is a field I am interested in. Finally, I regret residing in De Neve Plaza freshman year. A lot of the people on my floor were wealthy and very different from me. I could not relate to them and struggled to make friends.
